<FIRST>r i AM-China-Deng     11-12 0708</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Deng,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deng Calls on Military to Support Jiang</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senior leader Deng Xiaoping called on the
military Sunday to give its full support to Communist Party chief
Jiang Zemin, who replaced Deng as head of the party's Central
Military Commission.
   Deng, in a speech to senior military officers, said Jiang ``is
the qualified chairman of the military commission because he is the
qualified general secretary of the party,'' the official Xinhua
News Agency reported.
   It quoted Deng as saying Jiang was the nucleus of the party and
his appointment was a ``correct choice made by the whole party.''
   Jiang, a former Shanghai party boss who was named head of the
Communist Party in June, has no military connections and the
decision to name him chairman of the military commission may have
met resistance within the military hierarchy.
   Deng, 85, on Thursday announced his resignation from the
commission, the last official party post he held.
   He is certain to remain China's most powerful political figure
while he is in good health, but has stepped down from his official
positions to help pave the way for a transition to Jiang, his
chosen successor.
   Foreign diplomats say Jiang, with a weak power base in Beijing,
would have a difficult time surviving a power st Requested port out
of service. perSonics-Timberwolves, 3rd Ld - Writethru,0505
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Optional</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE NADEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Sports Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It looked like Win No. 2 for the expansion
Minnesota Timberwolves and a third straight loss for the road-weary
Seattle SuperSonics.
   Minnesota used a 16-2 spurt to take an 83-80 lead and had the
ball with nine minutes to go. But Sam Mitchell, who keyed the
Timberwolves' run, was called for traveling.
   Dale Ellis followed with a 3-point jumper that practically
deflated the Metrodome roof. The 21,702 fans let out a collective
groan, Seattle's Derrick McKey took over under the basket and the
Sonics used a 19-4 surge to win 108-97.
   ``We needed a basket desperately'' said Ellis, who has made more
3-pointers (486) than any other player in NBA history. ``We had
been down the court a few times and had come up empty-handed. I
like to take shots in times like that. I feel 3-pointers are
high-percentage shots.
   ``Three-pointers are like dunks. They can deflate an opponent.
They'll give up for a short spell and that's all it takes.''
   It's all it took for McKey to take over. He scored 10 of his 32
points during the decisive rally.
   ``He broke our backs,'' Wolves coach Bill Musselman said. ``We
tried everybody on him. It was tough to match up with him.''
   Said Minnesota's Tony Campbell: ``We went ahead, then this guy
started making everything. He shot from his ankles and it went in.''
   Seattle led 78-67 with 2:33 left in the third quarter, but
Mitchell scored eight of his career-high 31 points and Campbell
added six of his 30 during the run that gave the Timberwolves their
three-point lead.
   Ellis' 3-pointer was the first scoring of the fourth quarter for
the Sonics, who had committed turnovers their first five times down
the court.
   McKey followed with a 10-footer, Michael Cage dunked and Xavier
McDaniel made a short jumper before McKey scored eight straight
points to complete the spurt for a 99-87 lead.
   Seattle coach Bernie Bickerstaff said it was just a matter of
getting his starters back in the game. He felt it was necessary to
give them some rest after Thursday's five-overtime loss at
Milwaukee and Saturday's 109-102 defeat at Chicago.
   ``That was the only difference I could see,'' he said. ``When
players are fatigued, they revert to sloppy, playground basketball.
The team could have made excuses, but they responded. They executed
excellently down the stretch. Ellis hit his 3-pointer and we
exploited Derrick inside.''
   McDaniel added 26 points for the Sonics, whose three victories
this season include two over Minnesota.
   Before the loss at Chicago dropped its record to 2-3, Seattle
hadn't been under .500 since Nov. 30, 1988.
   For Minnesota, the defeat came two days after it beat
Philadelphia for its first-ever victory.
   Cage had 12 of his 18 points and 10 of his 16 rebounds in the
first half as the Sonics took a 58-49 halftime lead.
</TEXT>
