<FIRST>u a AM-DoubleShooting     11-12 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Double Shooting,0395</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paper: Man Held in Shooting of Pregnant Woman and Husband</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man sought in last month's shooting of a
pregnant woman and her husband has been arrested for a traffic
violation, it was reported Sunday.
   Police in the nearby community of Burlington, where the arrest
was made Saturday, refused to confirm a report in the Boston Sunday
Herald that William Bennett was wanted in the shooting.
   The attack, which prompted widespread news reports examining
Boston's crime problems, killed attorney Carol Stuart her baby, who
was delivered by Caesarean section. Her husband, Charles Stuart,
remains hospitalized.
   Bennett, 39, of Boston's Mission Hill section, was arrested at
the Burlington home of his girlfriend, said Burlington police Lt.
Arnold Christiansen. He said the arrest, for a traffic violation,
was made at the request of the Boston police and referred further
questions to that department. ``It was a routine arrest on a
traffic warrant,'' said Christiansen.
   Boston police refused to comment on the reports, and they
refused to confirm or deny they had Bennett in custody on any
charge, said Sgt. Al Dennehey said Saturday night.
   ``If he is in custody, we have not yet been notified,'' Dennehey
said Saturday night. ``To my knowledge, no one has been arrested
for that shooting.''
   The Herald quoted unnamed police sources as saying Bennett was a
suspect in the double shooting.
   The defendant's mother, Pauline Bennett, told the paper her son
was wanted in the attack.
   ``They say he's a suspect. He's been in trouble before. He knew
he was a suspect. He was nervous and upset about it,'' Pauline
Bennett said.
   Mrs. Stuart died after she was shot by a man who abducted the
couple as they left the inner-city Brigham and Women's Hospital,
where they had attended a birthing class. Charles Stuart was listed
in guarded condition after having surgery Saturday at Boston City
Hospital.
   The infant, Christopher Stuart, was delivered by Caesarean
section and clung to life for more than two weeks before succumbing
to a respiratory ailment Thursday. The medical examiner ruled his
death a homicide.
   Bennett has served separate prison terms for shooting two police
officers, the newspaper reported.
   Charles Stuart told police his assailant shot him because he
thought Stuart was a police officer.
</TEXT>
