<HEAD>Rebels Launch Offensive, Three Reported Dead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Leads with 10 grafs to UPDATE with more fighting, international
flights suspended, other details. Pickup 7th graf `The San...' ^By ANNIE
CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fighting raged in the capital
and provincial areas and interrupted international flights for a
second day Sunday in a major guerrilla offensive after peace talks
broke down. At least three people were reported dead and 40 wounded.
   Leftist rebels Saturday night attacked the residence of
right-wing President Alfredo Cristiani and other official buildings
and occupied several sectors of the northern part of San Salvador,
where fighting continued Sunday. He was reportedly not in danger.
   Casualty reports were incomplete, since ambulances were unable
to drive in some affected areas.
   Civilian sources contacted by telephone reported fighting in
four of 14 provinces, but there were no immediate official reports
of casualties.
   An airline employee who spoke on condition of anonymity said
international flights were suspended because two explosive devices
were found at the airport and the access road to the airport was
damaged due to guerrilla attacks.
   Military headquarters in the eastern cities of San Miguel and
Usulutan were attacked, said Col. Rene Ponce, chief of the joint
chiefs of staff.
   Ponce, speaking on the government's National Radio, said no one
was killed or wounded in the military installations.
   However, at least one guerrilla and two children were reported
killed in the fighting, which began early Saturday. The
government's Rosales Hospital said 40 civilians were admitted with
injuries.
   ``There are many people wounded by bullets and explosives, but
we have not gathered complete information because we have not been
able to evacuate the wounded, the combat is so intense,'' a Red
Cross spokesman said Saturday.
   Ponce said the most significant attacks were launched on the
private and official residences Cristiani; the home of the
president of the legislative assembly, Ricardo Alvarenga; the 1st
Infantry Brigade; the national police headquarters in the Mejicanos
neighborhood; the 3rd Infantry Brigade in San Miguel; and the 6th
Brigade in Usulutan.
   The San Salvador neighborhood where most of the country's top
military officers live also came under fire, he said.
   Ponce said Cristiani ``is under complete protection and at no
time was he in danger.''
   Alvarenga also escaped injury. However, the attack on his
residence left at least one guerrilla dead and at two security
guards wounded, according to civilian sources.
   The first guerrilla attack came Saturday morning when guerrillas
launched shells from homemade mortars at a barracks in northern San
Salvador, said Col. Carlos Carrillo, director of the National
Guard. He said one struck the installation, injuring three soldiers.
   Another mortar landed in a poor neighborhood, killing two
children and injuring five civilians, Carrillo said.
   Gunfire, explosions and sirens rang out throughout the city
Saturday night and into the early morning hours Sunday.
   Among the wounded was the 15-year-old daughter of Egyptian
ambassador Mahr Elkachess. He told The Associated Press by
telephone from a hospital that his daughter, Nadine, was undergoing
surgery and her condition was unknown.
   Ponce called the attacks ``irritations that only affected the
civilian population.'' He said the armed forces have ``responded
efficiently, rejecting the terrorist aggression.''
   The attacks came three days after the rebels' Farabundo Marti
National Liberation Front promised to intensify its decade-old
insurgency against the U.S.-backed government. More than 70,000
people have been killed.
   Recent peace talks between the government and the guerrilla
front broke down.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
