<FIRST>r i AM-MappaMundi     11-12 0343</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mappa Mundi,0357</SECOND>
<HEAD>Famous Map to Stay at Cathedral With Help From Getty's Son</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HEREFORD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hereford Cathedral has accepted a $4.8
million offer partly financed by oil heir John Paul Getty Jr. to
keep a unique 13th century map of the world off the auction block,
the cathedral announced.
   Dean Peter Haynes said Saturday the cathedral in Hereford,
western England, had agreed to a package of $1.6 million from Getty
and $3.2 million from the state-funded National Heritage Memorial
Fund.
   He said the money will be used to build a new museum on
cathedral grounds and set up a trust to safeguard the map and
ensure it is never sold.
   The plan is to be announced formally Monday.
   The Mappa Mundi, which shows Jerusalem at the center of a flat
world, is considered a national treasure. Its name means ``Map of
the World'' in Latin.
   The dean and the cathedral's governing authority announced a
year ago that the map would be auctioned off, possibly to foreign
buyers, for about $11 million to pay for repairs to the
900-year-old cathedral.
   The map was later withdrawn from auction after a national outcry.
   An alternate plan to collect money by selling public shares of
the map raised only $384,000. The project was scrapped.
   Under the latest plan, the map will be displayed with the
cathedral's other main treasure, a library of medieval books.
   ``The gain to the cathedral will be that there will be a
properly constructed building, sympathetic to the rest of the
cathedral,'' Haynes told reporters.
   ``The Mappa Mundi in the past has been simply in the north choir
aisle, and its place in a new building will allow it to be properly
safeguarded,'' he said.
   Getty, who lives in England, has given millions of dollars to
British institutions. His largest gift was $63 million in 1985 to
buy paintings for the National Gallery in London's Trafalgar Square.
   His father, J. Paul Getty, died in 1976 after creating a U.S.
oil empire. He left behind a fortune of $4 billion.
</TEXT>
