<FIRST>r i AM-EGermany-Israel     11-12 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EGermany-Israel,0687</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israel Has Difficulty Sharing German Happiness</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGEI SHARGORODSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There was one voice of discontent in the chorus
of praise for East Germany's decision to open its borders, one
country that could not share the happiness of Germans dancing on
the ruins of Berlin Wall.
   It was the Jewish state.
   Israel, which became home to about 100,000 survivors of the Nazi
Holocaust, had other ruins to remember.
   East Germany's decision to open the borders to the West came on
the anniversary of Kristallnacht, during which the Nazis destroyed
Jewish homes, stores and synagogues, killing 91 Jews and sending
30,000 to concentration camps.
   The night of Nov. 9-10, 1938, was named ``Crystal Night'' by the
Nazis for the shattered glass that covered the streets. In the dark
years that followed, the Nazis killed 6 million Jews.
   When the Jews saw modern-day Germans toasting champagne in the
streets, they could neither forget nor forgive.
   ``When I watched them on the screen, I was happy because of the
people's happiness, I could feel how happy they were ... and I told
myself: `But these are Germans,''' sociologist Yehudit Richter said
in an interview Saturday.
   Mrs. Richter's father was among the twins who suffered barbarous
genetic experiments at the hands of Nazi doctor Josef Mengele. Her
mother is a concentration camp survivor.
   ``I have never visited Germany and I shall never go there. I can
forgive on a personal level, but on the level of society, I shall
never forgive,'' Mrs. Richter said.
   Leading Israeli newspapers and analysts sounded a bitter note as
they described the events in Berlin, home to 175,000 Jews and one
of the world's largest Jewish communities before World War II.
About 150 Jews live in East Berlin today.
   ``Maybe Germany's reunfication, its climb to European
leadership, are unavoidable,'' the mass-circulation daily Yediot
Ahronot said in an editorial. ``But for God's sake, not in our
generation.''
   The state-run Israel Television interrupted Saturday's flow of
pictures from Germany to interview Gershom Schocken, the elderly
editor of Israel's Haaretz newspaper.
   ``It's very important that Germany stays divided,'' he declared.
``In the 20th century, Germany twice brought incomparable disasters
upon the world.''
   ``The German people of today seek peace, they are cultural and
friendly...but we cannot ignore the German potential that
implemented itself so terribly upon the Jews and other people. One
must hope such things would not be repeated in history, but we
cannot forget them.''
   Shlomo Aronson, a German-educated political scientist from the
Hebrew University, agreed.
   ``My only doubt about reunification is the historic tendency of
Germans, young and old ... to lose control once they are
powerful,'' he said. ``This is the thing that Jews and especially
the Israelis have to be conscious of. In this sense we do have a
right to be sceptical.''
   That skepticism was reflected in a cautious statement by Prime
Minister Yitzhak Shamir, who praised the changes in Eastern Europe
but said they could be dangerous.
   ``What is happening today in Eastern Europe is an earthquake ..
. They have not reached stability yet ... and that period of
instability carries many dangers,'' said Shamir, whose parents
perished in the Holocaust.
   Israel has never had formal contacts with East Germany because
of its denial of responsibility for Nazi Germany's crimes. Ties
with West Germany, Israel's second-largest trading partner after
the United States, experienced many upheavals.
   A reparations accord came in 1952, followed by the establishment
of diplomatic relations in 1965. Israel's ambivalence toward West
Germany reached its peak in 1981, when then-premier Menachem Begin
told Parliament:
   ``For what happened to the Jewish people in the 1930s and 1940s
in Europe, the entire German people is responsible.''
   No Israeli leader repeated such a claim since. But many Israelis
share the feeling.
   ``We see the wave of history flooding Eastern Europe,''
columnist Yosef Lapid wrote in the daily Maariv, ``and find
ourselves divided between our human identity and our Jewish
destiny.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891112-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-12-89 1203EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-EGermany-France     11-12 0671</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EGermany-France,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>French Fears Rise Over Spectre of Unified Germany</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The spectre of a reunified Germany, awakened by the
opening of the Berlin Wall last week, haunts Frenchmen who remember
German troops marching across the eastern frontier at the beginning
of two world wars.
   ``It seems to me that whenever the Germans are united, they are
united against us,'' comedian Guy Bedos told a French radio
interviewer after the wall was opened Thursday.
   This anxiety has been the motor driving French efforts to
integrate West Germany into a fully federal Europe unified
economically, politically and, perhaps, militarily after 1992.
   France, Italy and others believe that bringing West Germany
firmly into a tightly organized European Community will keep it
from pursuing its own interests as it did in 1870, 1914 and 1939.
   France, the current head of the 12-member European Community, is
bound to place events in Germany at the center of talks among heads
of state at the European Summit in Strasbourg next month.
   The summit was expected to be a showdown between the conflicting
visions of European unity held by French President Francois
Mitterrand and British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
   But last week's events are likely to fuel a common desire to
find compromise on issues such as monetary union and a European
social charter and to move quickly toward completing the plan for
unification.
   French leaders Friday urged that the European Community members
open their borders with the same speed as shown by East German
officials in opening the wall splitting Berlin.
   ``Democratization should be pursued first of all within East
Germany itself,'' said former conservative President Valery Giscard
d'Estaing, now a member of the European Parliament. ``And, during
this period, (I hope we) will not lose time in pursuing our own
union.''
   French angst is fed by the knowledge that West Germany _ big and
powerful with a population numerous and industrious _ already is a
formidable force.
   In the first half of this year, the country's gross national
product blasted ahead at a 4.6 percent annual rate, the quickest
rise in 13 years. Exports for the first seven months of 1989 were
18 percent higher than last year's record pace.
   West German business interests reach into all corners of Europe,
and in many markets it is Japan's main competitor.
   If joined with East Germany, the nation would have more than 80
million people out of a total Western European population of about
320 million and a gross domestic product almost as big as Britain's
and France's combined.
   It would have the biggest army in Europe outside the Soviet
Union _ a fact that has not gone unnoticed in Paris.
   ``Relations with Germany have been, since the beginning of the
century, a major problem,'' wrote political observer Alain
Peyrefitte in an editorial in the conservative daily Le Figaro.
``The two Germanys divided between NATO and the European Community
on the one side and the Warsaw Pact on the other, furnished a
solution to the problem.''
   ``All of this is now in question...'' and the balance of power
is about ``to be upset,'' he wrote.
   West Germany is already the chief Western trading partner of the
Soviet Union and its East bloc allies, and it is well positioned by
a number of factors, including language, to benefit from the new
free-market economies emerging in Poland and Hungary.
   France, like other European Community members, worries that West
German attraction to the east will dampen its enthusiasm for
European integration.
   Jacques Delors, president of the European Commission, has said
he fears West Germany might be ``tempted by a destiny other than
the construction of Europe.''
   Delors met behind closed doors in Brussels on Friday night with
the 17 European Community commissions to discuss German
reunification, the first debate ever held on the possibility.
   Discussions focused on ways to incorporat East Germany _ and
possibly other East Bloc countries _ into the Common Market
framework.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
