<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan     11-12 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rockets Rocket Attack Kills 13; Salang Highway Reportedly Cut Off</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rocket slammed into a house while
three generations of a family were having tea Sunday, killing 13
people, witnesses said. It was one of 11 rocket attacks reported by
the government.
   An additional three people were injured in the other attacks.
   Elsewhere, U.S.-backed rebel forces reportedly closed the
highway again connecting the capital to the Soviet Union, sparking
new fears of shortages. The government denied the Salang Highway
was closed, but soldiers said buses bound for a provincial capital,
Mazar-e-Sharif, had been turned back and that fighting near the
Salang tunnel was fierce.
   The fatal rocket attack occurred at 2:30 p.m. in the northwest
corner of Kabul, across the street from the Continental Hotel where
many foreign reporters stay. Witnesses said the rocket went through
the roof of a two-story house and exploded in the living room.
   Three generations of a family had just sat down to tea, they
said. The shrapnel from the rocket killed everybody in the room,
they said.
   The United States supplies rockets to the Moslem guerrillas, who
have been fighting the Soviet-backed government more than a decade.
It could not be immediately determined what kind of missile hit the
house, but people in the neighborhood blamed the United States.
   ``Tell the Americans that we are sick of this war,'' said a
woman who lives next door to the stricken house. ``These could have
been my children and my parents dead here. This is not a war for
freedom; it is a war against the people.''
   The attacks Sunday marked the first time in four days that
rockets have hit Kabul. On Saturday, the government claimed it was
clearing the guerrillas from the hills surrounding the capital.
   Since June, rocket attacks on Kabul have killed about 400
people. Half the victims have been children, according to the
International Committee of the Red Cross. The government says the
rebels are responsible for the attacks, but the rebels deny it.
   The frequent attacks are souring the population's once strong
support for the rebels, or mujahedeen, who are credited with
chasing the Soviet Red Army from Afghanistan. The Soviets withdrew
the last of their troops from Afghanistan in February.
   ``Before the rockets began, the people had hope for a good
change in Afghanistan,'' said Trina Nawabi, a doctor. ``Now, they
feel the mujahedeen have let them down.''
   Soldiers with knowledge of the Salang Highway said rebel and
government forces were fighting north of the town of Carikar on the
highway. They said rebel forces succeeded in shutting down the
highway near the town of Salang.
   Soldiers said government troops would probably open the road in
one or two days.
   ``It is always like this,'' said a captain in the government
army. ``They have it for a few days, we have it for a week.''
   The guerrillas closed the highway for 10 days late last month,
causing prices of flour and gasoline to jump 50 percent because
supplies could not be driven in from the Soviet border.
   Since it opened again in early November, more than 2,000 trucks
have rolled into the capital, Kabul.
   Soldiers said thousands of trucks carrying food are waiting to
head south from Hayratan, the main depot for goods from the Soviet
Union. Afghan news reports say Moscow has sent more than 200,000
metric tons of goods via Hayratan since the last Soviet soldiers
withdrew from Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
