<FIRST>r i AM-Ethiopia-Rebels     11-12 0202</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ethiopia-Rebels,0209</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Announces Second Set of Ethiopia Peace Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethiopia's government and rebels from the Tigre
province wrapped up a preliminary meeting over the weekend and will
hold a second set of peace talks next month, the Italian government
said Sunday.
   The rebels and the Marxist government held a week of preliminary
talks in Rome that ended Saturday, with the Italian government
acting as host and observer.
   The Italian Foreign Ministry said in a statement that the talks
took place in an ``open and constructive atmosphere, despite the
presence of difficulties.''
   The discussions were aimed at clearing the way for formal peace
negotiations.
   The talks between the government and the Tigre People's
Liberation Front will resume Dec. 12 in Rome, the ministry said.
   The Tigrean rebels have been fighting for 14 years to win
greater autonomy. They have scored several major battlefield
victories in recent weeks.
   The government of President Mengistu Haile Mariam opened
preliminary peace talks with a second major rebel group, the
Eritrean People's Liberation Front, in September. They are
scheduled to resume in Nairobi, Kenya, later this month.
   Italy invaded Ethiopia in 1936, but the Italian forces were
defeated by the Allies in 1941.
