<DOCNO> AP891112-0028 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-12-89 1338EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Spending-Taxes     11-12 0802</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spending-Taxes,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Partial Gramm-Rudman Cuts Now Seem Likely to Stick</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congressional leaders deadlocked with White
House officials in their search for $14 billion in budget savings
now seem ready to let the guillotine of the Gramm-Rudman law do
some of the work for them.
   The willingness to permanently retain a portion of the $16.1
billion in cuts to most federal programs imposed last month by the
balanced-budget law comes from Democrats and Republicans alike, and
reverses congressional sentiment that prevailed until recently.
   ``If that becomes the litmus test or quid pro quo for the
administration agreeing to ... (a deficit-reduction bill), then
it's not off the table,'' Senate Budget Committee Chairman James
Sasser, D-Tenn., said last Thursday.
   The ranking Republican on the Senate budget panel, Pete Domenici
of New Mexico, said bipartisan talks aimed at finding a way to
reduce this year's projected $116 billion shortfall are moving ``in
the direction of a compromise that will have some across-the-board
cuts'' in federal spending.
   The only real question at this point appears to be the degree to
which the cuts will be left in place. As a rule of thumb, roughly
$1 billion is saved for each month the cuts are retained.
   Turning to partial Gramm-Rudman slashes for some savings is the
latest twist to ongoing Democratic-Republican efforts to do one of
two things. Each side wants to either agree to a deficit-reduction
bill coupled with some savings from Gramm-Rudman cuts, or to find a
way to blame the other party if their efforts fail and the full
Gramm-Rudman reductions remain in effect all year.
   The balanced-budget law triggered the $16.1 billion in cuts on
Oct. 16, when Congress and President Bush failed to agree to a plan
to shrink the deficit to $110 billion. At the time, the working
assumption on Capitol Hill was that the cuts would be rolled back
when a plan to reduce the shortfall was sculpted.
   But after weeks of fruitless searching for a deficit-reduction
deal, the Gramm-Rudman cuts remain in place. Bush says he'd prefer
retaining the across-the-board slashes to enactment of the
budget-cutting bills passed by the Senate and House, which he
complains contain billions of dollars in phony savings, such as
shifting payments out of the fiscal year.
   Although the Gramm-Rudman reductions have barely been felt so
far, their pain will become more apparent if left intact much
longer as agencies are forced to save money. The law has imposed
4.3 percent reductions in defense spending and 5.3 percent cuts in
most domestic programs, excluding Social Security and initiatives
for the poor.
   To avoid that scenario, Democrats want to move a
deficit-reduction measure through Congress by Thanksgiving that
restores most of the Gramm-Rudman reductions _ a plan they believe
puts pressure on Bush.
   ``If the president wants to sign it, which I think would be the
responsible thing to do, I'd applaud him,'' said Sasser. ``If he
chooses to veto it, that's regrettable and he'll have to take the
consequences of that.''
   Some lawmakers do not see things that way. Sen. Bob Packwood,
R-Ore., ranking Republican on the Finance Committee, has been a
staunch defender of Bush's threat to veto an inadequate
deficit-reduction measure and leave the Gramm-Rudman cuts intact.
   Packwood wrote to Bush last week that retaining the Gramm-Rudman
cuts is ``not the worst outcome'' is the alternative is a
deficit-cutting bill ``that relies upon budget gimmicks and
accounting devices, contains almost no long-term deficit reduction,
and sets the stage for a true budget crisis next year.''
   Indeed, lawmakers are drawing differing conclusions about just
how damaging retention of the Gramm-Rudman cuts will be.
   Ranking House Budget Committee Republican Bill Frenzel of
Minnesota circulated an analysis last week concluding that the cuts
are ``a mixed bag.'' The Defense Department could have to pare its
active-duty personnel by 170,000 troops, but the Federal Aviation
Administration would be able to juggle its budget and protect air
traffic controllers, Frenzel wrote.
   Yet Rep. Silvio Conte of Massachusetts, ranking Republican on
the House Appropriations Committee, said the cuts ``will have
severe negative impacts on hundreds of programs.'' He wrote of 2
million farmers facing support payment reductions, AIDS service
cuts, and 250,000 fewer Pell Grants to college students.
   One key impediment to Congress' budget work appears ready to be
laid aside for the rest of the year next week.
   The Senate plans votes Tuesday and Wednesday on a proposal to
cut the tax on capital gains, a plan Bush has fought for all year.
If GOP supporters of the plan lose _ as expected _ they have
promised to not raise the issue again until next year.
   Republican insistence on trying to attach the plan to crucial
budget bills has slowed work on those measures in recent weeks.
</TEXT>
