<FIRST>r w AMS-CrimeStatistics     11-12 0444</FIRST>
<SECOND>AMS-Crime Statistics,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release at 6 p.m. EST - time set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>Violent Crime Up 5 Percent In First Half Of This Year, FBI Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 7 percent jump in robberies paced a 5
percent increase in violent crime during the first half of this
year, according to FBI statistics released Sunday.
   Overall, reported crimes went up 3 percent during the first half
of 1989 from the same period last year, with each of the nation's
four regions posting increases, the bureau said in its Uniform
Crime Report.
   By comparison, the FBI's overall crime index increased 1 percent
during both the first halves of 1987 and 1988 and went up 8 percent
during the first six months of 1986.
   There was a 4 percent increase in overall crime reports in both
the South and the West. Crime went up 2 percent in the Midwest and
3 percent in the Northeast, the report said.
   Among various categories of crime, the biggest increase was an
11 percent jump in motor vehicle thefts, followed by a 7 percent
hike in robberies.
   Murders increased 5 percent over the same period last year,
while aggravated assaults went up 4 percent.
   The number of murders in the first half of 1988 was virtually
unchanged from the same period in 1987, when there was a 2 percent
drop from the same period in 1986, the bureau said.
   The number of murders went up 7 percent in the South and 6
percent in the West. There was a 1 percent increase in reported
homicides in the Northeast and a 4 percent increase in the Midwest.
   Murders increased 15 percent in cities with populations between
500,000 and a million. Homicides increased 10 percent in cities
with populations between 100,000 and 250,000.
   But the increase in murders was not confined to large urban
areas.
   Killings increased 11 percent in cities with with populations
between 25,000 and 50,000 and 7 percent in towns with populations
under 10,000.
   Suburban counties reported a 6 percent decrease in murders.
   The West had the biggest increase in motor vehicle thefts _ 16
percent _ followed by 10 percent increases in both the South and
the Northeast. Motor vehicle thefts went up 5 percent in the
Midwest.
   The overall 11 percent increase followed an 8 percent jump in
motor vehicle thefts during the same period in 1988.
   Larcenies and thefts went up 3 percent between January and June
while the number of reported burglaries was off 1 percent.
   Forcible rapes dropped 2 percent and reports of arson went down
4 percent from the first six months of 1988.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
