<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-SisterCities     11-12 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Sister Cities,0490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Little Towns Swap Populations For a Day</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARTHUR MAX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KATHARINENBERG, East Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The line that carved Germany
into two nations could not have come closer to the farmhouse where
Waleska Von Hagen was born.
   ``My father's land was divided down the middle,'' she said.
   On Sunday, Mrs. Von Hagen was among hundreds of people from the
little West German town of Wanfried who suddenly decided to push
across the border to look at the little East German village of
Katharinenberg.
   Much to the dizzying confusion of border guards, hundreds of
equally curious Katharinenberg residents traveled the four miles to
look at Wanfried.
   Authorities announced early Sunday that the road between the two
border towns would be one of the new crossings opened for the first
time in three decades.
   Hundreds of East Germans began crossing into West Germany to
visit Wanfried and gawk at its relative opulence.
   At Katharinenberg, guards stamped passports or identity cards of
East Germans at a makeshift control point but were overwhelmed by
the numbers and gave up within an hour.
   Although the open border was meant more for East Germans who had
been denied travel privileges for 28 years, Wanfried residents were
eager to look at their East German sister city.
   Hundreds of townspeople from Wanfried, which has 3,000
residents, walked up a wooded lane to the wire-mesh fence to cheer
the East Germans as they crossed into the West German town.
   Several East Germans on foot waved hand-printed signs reading,
``Freiheit,'' the German word for ``freedom.''
   Suddenly, a crowd of West Germans surged forward past the
guards, who watched with stunned looks, and began heading East.
   ``Now we're going to see how you live on the other side,'' said
one West German to a man walking in the other direction.
   ``You won't find anybody in Katharinenberg,'' the East German
responded. ``They have all gone across the border.''
   One of the first West Germans to reach this village was Mrs. Von
Hagen, who said she was born in a farmhouse just over the border on
the West German side.
   She said Gen. George S. Patton and a Soviet officer met in her
father's living room and signed the agreement that drew the border
for this region.
   ``I've never been able to come here before. We were never
allowed,'' she said, looking at the simple village homes.
   Asked what she thought of the East German village, she said,
``It's like going back 40 years in time.''
   Border guards abandoned any attempt to stop the tide of laughing
and waving West Germans heading to Katharinenberg.
   ``You have to have your passport. The regulations are still the
same,'' an East German guard told West Germans who bothered to ask.
``But at the moment we can't do anything.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
