<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-Election     11-12 0717</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Election,0738</SECOND>
<HEAD>Undecided Vote Plagues Sandinistas</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega's biggest
problem in his party's campaign to retain power may not be the
U.S.-backed political opposition, but the large number of undecided
voters.
   The results of three opinion polls put the undecided figure at
35 percent to 46 percent heading into the Feb. 25 balloting.
   This could lend credence to charges by Washington and opposition
groups that Ortega this month ended a cease-fire with the Contras
in order to create a crisis and have an excuse to call off
elections the Sandinistas fear they might lose.
   The thinking is that if the leftist Sandinista government has
not won support from a clear majority after 10 years in power, it
will be hard-pressed to do so in the brief time remaining before
the general elections.
   In all three polls, those who said they will vote in the
elections ranged from 78.4 percent to 95 percent.
   Ortega had been leading in most polls except the latest one, in
which publisher Violeta Barrios de Chamorro was favored by 42.8
percent of those surveyed, to Ortega's 21.3 percent.
   Still, even in that poll, 35 percent of the respondents were
either unsure of who they would for vote or did not answer the
question. The remaining .9 percent favored five other presidential
candidates from tiny parties.
   That poll, released last week, was conducted Oct. 23-30 by the
Costa Rican firm of Borge and Associates for La Prensa, the
Nicaraguan opposition daily owned by Mrs. Chamorro's family; and El
Nuevo Herald, the Spanish-language edition of The Miami Herald.
   It surveyed 1,284 Nicaraguans nationwide and had a margin of
error of 4 percent.
   Delegations from the Sandinistas and the U.S.-backed rebels are
to resume negotiations Monday at the Organization of American
States in Washington.
   Ortega is intent on having the estimated 12,000 Contras
demobilize from their Honduran jungle camps before the elections.
The Contras have said they will stay put until the elections take
place.
   As an incentive, Ortega has offered to resume at the end of this
month the cease-fire he suspended Nov. 1, after it had been in
effect since March 1988.
   Renewed fighting between Sandinistas and Contras would make
campaigning impossible. But critics say the Sandinistas want the
Contras eliminated as a pressure force in order to have a freer
hand should election results not be in their favor.
   Two other polls have given Ortega the upper hand over Mrs.
Chamorro.
   One poll was conducted Oct. 2-7 by the Nicaraguan firm ECO for
the Central American University in Managua. In it, 78.4 percent of
the 4,114 people answering said they would vote in the elections.
   Of those surveyed, 36.5 percent said they would vote for the
Sandinistas, 18.1 percent for the opposition and 41.8 percent were
undecided or did not answer the question.
   In another poll, by the Nicaraguan Institute of Public Opinion,
83 percent of the 1,157 people surveyed said they would vote.
Twenty-six percent said they would vote for Ortega; 21 percent for
Mrs. Chamorro; and 46 percent were undecided or did not answer the
question.
   That poll was conducted Sept. 27-Oct. 2.
   By the same token, the percentage of undecideds sends a strong
message to Mrs. Chamorro's 14-party bloc, the National Opposition
Union: that Nicaraguans do not consider it a good alternative to
the Sandinistas.
   ``That showing of people who pretend they don't know who they're
going to vote for is a Latin American phenomenon,'' said a Latin
American diplomat of long experience. ``What these people are
saying is `We're going to vote for the least bad (candidate),' and
it's the decisive vote in any election.
   ``That also shows clearly the wasting away of Sandinista fervor
over these 10 years. This is due to several reasons, but the main
one is their not having been able to solve ... the socio -economic
problem.''
   ``Everything Will Be Better,'' the Sandinista campaign slogan,
is an acknowledgement that the economy must be improved. But the
promise rings hollow when living conditions are on an unrelenting
downslide with no apparent end in sight.
   Ortega's government has been battling hyperinflation with a
tough austerity program that has slashed government spending and
laid off more than 30,000 public employees this year.
</TEXT>
