<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Military Bjt   11-12 0520</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Military, Bjt,0533</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yazov Condemns Anti-Army Protests; Latvians Ask for Alternative Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAREY GOLDBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense Minister Dmitri T. Yazov, confronted by a
growing movement against the draft, lashed out at ``anti-army
manifestations'' and ruled out change in conscription rules, the
official Tas news agency said Sunday.
   The report came a day after the Latvian Supreme Soviet, in a
move that carried more symbolic than legal force, voted to allow
alternative service to conscientious objectors in the Baltic
republic.
   Tass said Yazov ``condemned anti-army manifestations which
recently spread in some regions of the country _ calls to refuse
service in the army, attempts to evade call-up into the armed
forces, blockade of call-up stations, etc.''
   The Tass report indicated Yazov was not receptive to proposals
from groups in various Soviet republics to allow soldiers to serve
only in their home regions. He said the draft ``would continue to
develop according to the principles of extra-territoriality.''
   Nearly all Soviet men between 18 and 25 years old are required
to serve at least two years in the armed forces. Students were
granted deferments and partial exemptions from service this year,
but Yazov and Marshal Sergei Akhromeyev, President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's top military adviser, have made clear there will be no
shift to a volunteer army in the near future.
   The Soviet Union's standing army of about 4 million is about
halfway through a unilateral reduction of 500,000 troops announced
by Gorbachev in December.
   Yazov cited the Baltic region, the Caucasus republics and parts
of Moldavia, where he said anti-draft actions were strongest. All
have strong grassroots movements pushing for more independence from
Moscow.
   In the Caucasus republic of Georgia, more than 200 youths
protesting the draft have been staging sit-ins near government
buildings in recent days, activists said.
   The popular fronts of Latvia, Estonia and Lithuania are pushing
for their youths to serve only in the Baltics, and a small group of
protesters backing such regional service demonstrated in front of
the Estonian Parliament in Tallinn over the weekend.
   Azerbaijani activists charge that too many of the republic's
youths die in the service, and Latvians and other groups have
similar complaints.
   An empty coffin to symbolize deaths among Latvian soldiers was
brought to the republic's Supreme Soviet parliament during the
weekend debate on the alternative service law for conscientious
objectors, and mothers demonstrated outside the building, said Aris
Jansons, a Latvian newspaper editor.
   Jansons, political editor of the youth paper Padomju Jaunatne,
said a parliamentarian told him an amendment on alternative service
is being prepared in Moscow. But he said it focuses more on service
in construction battalions and other non-combat units.
   Speaking in a telephone interview from Riga, Jansons said the
Latvian measure was essentially ``a gesture'' to make its wishes
known, because the legislative body does not have the authority to
change Soviet military law.
   The presidium of the national Supreme Soviet last week put
Latvia and three other republics that have passed sovereignty laws
on notice that they are expected to bring their laws in line with
national policy and the constitution.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
