<FILEID>AP-NR-11-12-89 1549EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ReaganLibrary     11-12 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reagan Library,0620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Presidential Foundation Asks Sony for $1 Million Library Donation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One year after its ground-breaking, the
Ronald Reagan library has far exceeded its $45 million fund-raising
goal and is still looking for donations including $1 million from
Japan's Sony Corp.
   The latest palatial presidential library, under construction
atop a suburban hillside 45 miles northwest of the city, will also
be the last of such grand proportions thanks to a bill Reagan
signed while president.
   At 153,000 square feet, the Spanish-style Ronald Reagan
Presidential Library will dwarf even the largest of the
presidential museums _ the 100,000-square-foot Lyndon Johnson
shrine in Texas.
   Presidential libraries are built with private funds and
presented as gifts to the United States, which operates the museums
at taxpayer expense. The National Archives and Records
Administration will run the Reagan library with an annual budget of
about $1.5 million.
   The presidential library system, inaugurated by Franklin D.
Roosevelt, costs taxpayers about $16 million a year.
   ``Today's system makes each former president try to outdo his
predecessor and you end up with huge marble pyramids more fitting
as monuments to the pharaohs,'' Sen. Lawton Chiles, D-Fla.,
complained when he sponsored a 1986 bill limiting the size of such
libraries.
   It was Reagan who signed the Chiles bill limiting presidential
libraries to a single building of not more than 70,000 feet. His
own was exempted.
   The Reagan foundation refuses to identify donors, many of whom
gave in response to a $2.5 million direct-mail and telemarketing
campaign _ common in presidential library fund raising.
   Foundation records show it with assets of $58 million as of Dec.
31, 1988, the latest figures available, said Sam Williams,
spokesman for the Registry of Charitable Trusts, an arm of the
state Department of Justice.
   However, Reagan spokesman Mark Weinberg confirmed last week that
the foundation recently asked Japan-based Sony Corp. for a $1
million donation.
   ``Representatives of the foundation have had contact with a
number of American and foreign businesses about donating to the
library and Sony is one of them,'' he said.
   The foundation wants $1 million worth of video equipment to
enhance the library's value as a research center, but Sony
spokesman Tsutomu Sugiyama said a decision hadn't been made.
   ``The Reagans want this to be the best of the presidential
libraries ... state of the art,'' said Weinberg. He said organizers
are seeking funds in excess of the initial $45 million goal so
there will be endowment money to invest and bring income to the
library.
   The former president and his wife, Nancy, were the hosts in
Japan last month of the Fujisankei Communications Group, a Japanese
media company. Reagan was reportedly paid $2 million for that trip,
which included two speeches and attendance at a concert to benefit
the Reagan library.
   The Reagan library, located on a 100-acre site above the Ventura
County bedroom community of Simi Valley, will be the repository for
an expected 62 million papers, exceeding Richard Nixon's record 44
million.
   Set to open in the spring of 1991, the library will include
underground storage, a museum and research materials depicting the
Reagan administration and events during his Washington years.
   Reagan helped break ground Nov. 21, 1988, for the library that
will house his White House papers, saying at the time he hoped
historians and scholars examining his eight-year presidency would
``judge our efforts well.''
   Meanwhile, about 70 miles to the east, the Richard Nixon
Presidential Library is about half-completed on a site in the
Orange County community of Yorba Linda. Dedication is set for June
21, 1990.
</TEXT>
