<FIRST>r i AM-AbuNidal     11-12 0739</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abu Nidal,0761</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palestinian Officials Confirm Split in Abu Nidal's Group</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AHMED MANTASH</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian officials confirmed Sunday
that some 150 guerrillas have been killed in a 14-month power
struggle among dissidents of Libyan-backed terrorist mastermind Abu
Nidal.
   The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
victims included 20 senior officials of the Fatah-Revolutionary
Council, which Abu founded in 1973 after he broke away from Yasser
Arafat's Palestine Liberation Organization.
   The sources spoke in the Ein el-Hilweh refugee camp, the main
Lebanon power base of guerrillas loyal to Arafat. They said the 20
officials were shot by Abu Nidal, whose real name is Sabri
el-Banna, or his bodyguards at his home in Tripoli, Libya, and
buried in the backyard.
   Most of the others were killed in various refugee camps in
Lebanon, they said.
   The sources were commenting on reports about the bloody split
published Sunday in The New York Times. The newspaper cited
dissident Fatah-Revolutionary Council leaders, PLO officials and
Arab diplomats for its reports.
   The paper said most of the 20 leaders killed were ``lured into
Abu Nidal's house near Tripoli on the pretext of discussing policy
matters, taken by surprise and killed in the house.
   ``Then they were buried right there. Abu Nidal and his hirelings
poured the cement over their bodies themselves,'' the Times quoted
a dissident it identified as Abdul-Rahman Issa as saying.
   Abu Nidal tops the most wanted lists in the United States and
Europe for several terrorist attacks, including the 1986 bombing of
a synagogue in Istanbul, in which 21 people were killed, and the
1985 attacks at Rome and Vienna airports in which 20 people were
killed and 120 wounded.
   Abu Nidal also was behind the assassination of dozens of
moderate PLO officials who advocated peace with Israel.
   The PLO officials in Ein el-Hilweh said Issa and three other
members of the group's 10-man Politburo, including the spokesman,
Atef Abu Bakr, quit after Abu Nidal murdered Mustafa Murad in
Tripoli on Oct. 17, 1988.
   Murad, better known as Abu Nizar, had been Abu Nidal's closest
aide since the split from the PLO.
   PLO sources had reported a schism in the ranks of Abu Nidal's
group since mid-1987 mainly because of his totalitarian policies
and insistence on maintaining absolute control over finances.
   The group's money came mainly from Libyan leader Col. Moammar
Gadhafi and from a string of ransom kidnappings staged by Abu
Nidal's men against activists of humanitarian organizations in
south Lebanon in the last three years, according to Abu Bakr and
Issa.
   The two men have issued separate statements from Algiers,
Algeria, in the past few months in which they stressed the group's
financial corruption.
   Fatah-Revolutionary Council holds five Belgians and a French
woman hostage. The group said the six were seized Nov. 8, 1987,
aboard a French yacht off the Israeli-occupied Gaza Strip. It
accused them of spying for Israel.
   Two Swiss officials of the International Committee of the Red
Cross were kidnapped in Sidon on Oct. 6. They are believed held at
an Abu Nidal base in Majdalyoun on Sidon's eastern outskirts.
   Abu Nidal's activists also are believed to have kidnapped some
of the other 16 Westerners held in Lebanon and to have sold them to
pro-Iranian Moslem factions.
   Issa and Abu Bakr have said Murad was shot in the presence of
Majed Atta, the husband of Abu Nidal's niece.
   His widow, Subhia Murad, has accused Abu Nidal of shooting her
husband and burying him in a Fatah-Revolutionary Council camp
outside Tripoli, an account The New York Times said was
corroborated by unnamed Arab associates.
   At the camp, Abu Nidal built a new room for his house on top of
the spot where two other senior commanders were buried in concrete
after being killed by him late last year, the Times said.
   Haj Abu Mousa, the group's top military trainer, was lured to
Abu Nidal's house earlier in 1988 and killed in the same manner.
   The reports said the Tripoli killings touched off a campaign of
assassinations among the rival wings of the groups in which some
130 people have been killed in south Lebanon and in the northern
camps of Baddawi and Nahr el-Bared in the last three months.
   They said Abu Nidal has suspended the group's Politburo and
transferred its powers to the 50-man Central Committee after
appointing Atta as its second secretary. Abu Nidal is the first
secretary, they added.
</TEXT>
