<FIRST>r w AM-US-GermanChanges     11-12 0624</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-German Changes,600</SECOND>
<HEAD>East German Changes Hold Pitfalls for U.S. Defense Planners</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-East Germany</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEXANDER G. HIGGINS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opening of the Berlin Wall has brought joy
to the public but poses problems for U.S. defense planners trying
to maintain the military balance in Europe, experts say.
   ``There's so much euphoria, people will tend to think it's all
over,'' said Raymond L. Garthoff of the Brookings Institution.
   ``We need some sort of policy ... to preserve the military
balance in Europe,'' said Robert Lieber, a government professor at
Georgetown University. He urged a force cut on both sides, along
the lines of the conventional force reduction talks underway in
Vienna.
   Rapid change in East Germany underscores the need for stability
in Central Europe, the flashpoint for two world wars in this
century, said Garthoff and Lieber, echoing a view widely held among
defense officials.
   ``From 1871 to 1945 the politics of Europe were highly
unstable,'' and the main problem was a very powerful Germany, said
Lieber.
   U.S. officials face the followng questions, the experts said:
   _How to react to a possible reunification of East and West
Germany for the first time since the defeat of Nazi Germany in 1945.
   _Whether West Germany will be able to accommodate East German
refugees. An estimated 200,000 already have arrived in the West
this year.
   _How to encourage other East European countries to move toward
democracy and free-market economies.
   The pace of change appeared to be speeding up rather than
slowing down, with the resignation on Friday of Bulgarian communist
leader Todor Zhivkov after 35 years in power, indicating a shift
toward reform there.
   That would leave Czechoslovakia and Romania as the only two
members of the Warsaw Pact yet to start reforms.
   ``I suspect there will be some move fairly soon in
Czechoslovakia, too,'' leaving Romania even more isolated, said
Garthoff, who was U.S. ambassador to Bulgaria from 1977 to 1979. He
said he didn't expect changes in Romania as long President Nicolae
Ceausescu retains a strong hand.
   The European balance could be tipped by a unilateral Western
reduction in forces that leaves the Soviet Union dominant in the
region, or a decision by East Germany to unite with West Germany
and withdraw from the Warsaw Pact.
   Despite a unilateral Soviet troop reduction in Eastern Europe
announced last year, Western government officials say the Soviets
have superior conventional forces in Europe.
   Soviet experts, however, claim there is a rough equivalence when
sophisticated Western aircraft and other weapons are included.
   President Bush and his top advisers have insisted that caution
is the wisest policy in the face of rapid change in Eastern Europe.
   ``The best way to keep America and the West free is to keep
ourselves strong,'' Bush said in a speech last Friday.
   Bush also promised to ``seize every chance'' to encourage
democracy in Eastern Europe, but he and his top aides say that
despite Soviet Bloc claims that reform is permanent, hard-liners
could return.
   ``I don't think it's going to be reversible, but it may be,''
Secretary of State James A. Baker III said PBS-TV's
``MacNeil-Lehrer News Hour.'' ``That's why we must continue to
maintain our strength, our will.''
   The prospect of German reunification arouses great concern among
U.S. and Western European defense officials.
   ``The major pitfall is whether or not we do find that events
lead us the to reunification of Germany,'' said retired General
Bernard Rogers, the former NATO commander.
   East German Ambassador Gerhard Herder told a news conference he
could dream of German reunification, but not in the foreseeable
future.
   The main obstacle, he said, is that East and West Germany are
``integrated into military alliances guaranteeing a stable balance
of power'' in Europe.
</TEXT>
