<HEAD>Moldavian Activists Gather Signatures for Leadership to Resign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Activists in the Moldavian capital of Kishinev
canceled a rally planned for Sunday and instead circulated
petitions calling for the local leadership to resign, members of
the southwestern republic's People's Front said.
   People's Front leader Ion Hadyrka spurred the petition drive
with a speech on Moldavian television Saturday night, demanding
removal of conservatives in the top government echelons.
   Hadyrka also denied the People's Front was to blame for a brawl
Friday between police and protesters that left nearly 200 injured,
Natalia Pascal, the group's spokeswoman, said in a telephone
interview.
   Conflicting accounts of the clash aggravated a growing
confrontation between local government leaders and the People's
Front, a group formed last year to press for the rights of ethnic
Moldavians in the republic of 4.2 million that borders Romania.
   The republic's Communist Party Politburo charged that the
People's Front was a ``serious destabilizing factor which
aggravates the situation in Soviet Moldavia,'' and it accused the
group's supporters of ``joining in an open struggle to topple the
legitimate government.''
   People's Front members say they tried to stop the clash.
   Friday's injury count was raised from 83 police to 142, said
Fyodor Angeli, director of the Moldavian news agency, ATEM, in a
telephone interview from Kishinev. Forty-six protesters were also
reported injured and four of the police were in critical condition,
he said.
   More than 15,000 security troops were brought in by bus and
plane to Kishinev and armored personnel carriers could be seen on
the city's outskirts, Ms. Pascal said.
   Trouble in Kishinev began Nov. 7, the day marking the 1917
Bolshevik revolution that brought Communists to power. Protesters
blocked the military part of the traditional parade, and a People's
Front spokesman charged that police beat many would-be protesters.
   On Friday night, a crowd of several thousand gathered outside
the Interior Ministry headquarters in downtown Kishinev demanding
the release of about 20 people arrested Nov. 7. The crowd threw
stones and gasoline bombs at police, who responded with truncheons
and water cannons. Police finally used tear gas and fired into the
air to break up the crowd.
