<FIRST>r a AM-BoatPerson-Chemist     11-12 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Boat Person-Chemist,0578</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese College Student Wins Award For Chemical Research</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STATE COLLEGE, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six years after escaping Vietnam
aboard a 30-foot, wooden fishing boat, Son-Binh Nguyen made a
research discovery as a summer intern at DuPont that could improve
the way nylon is made.
   DuPont rewarded Nguyen last month with its Achievement Award,
the first college undergraduate ever to receive the honor from the
Delaware-based chemical giant's research and development department.
   Nguyen, a 20-year-old Penn State University senior majoring in
chemistry and physics, plays down his research efforts.
   ``It's luck as far as I'm concerned,'' he said recently.
   The 20-year-old's findings could potentially improve the way
chemicals used in manufacturing nylon are prepared and save the
company millions of dollars, said Ronald McKinney, Nguyen's
supervisor at DuPont.
   ``Son-Binh identified a problem that the company may not have
fully appreciated before and he also came up with a possible
solution,'' McKinney said.
   ``Whether that solution ends up being something used in the
plant is not clear yet. But it certainly is under serious
consideration. I think it looks very promising,'' he said.
   After several unsuccessful attempts to escape, Nguyen made it
out of Vietnam with about 20 others in March 1983 aboard his
uncle's boat bound for Malaysia. His parents were left behind.
   ``When I escaped, I don't even know if I live or not,'' said
Nguyen. ``A small boat in a big ocean, pirates, the government
coast guard. It very likely I might die.''
   They were rescued three days later. The group spent 13 months in
refugee camps in Malaysia and the Philippines before being allowed
into the United States.
   Nguyen and his brother Tran-Son, now 18, went to an aunt and
uncle already living in Williamsport.
   Although he didn't speak English very well, Nguyen was placed in
the regular curriculum at Williamsport High School.
   He got two jobs after school working from 2:30 p.m. until
midnight.
   ``He's an exceptionally talented, dedicated student,'' said Mary
Bennardi, who taught Nguyen English at Williamsport High School.
   At Penn State, Nguyen spends 20 to 25 hours a week in the
chemistry laboratory and takes eight or nine courses a semester.
   ``The work is exciting,'' he said.
   Nguyen is ``one of the hardest working students I've ever met,''
said Gregory Geoffroy, a chemistry professor who is dean of the
College of Science.
   Nguyen wants to do advanced studies in chemistry when he
graduates in May.
   He also expects to become a U.S. citizen next spring and is
trying to get his parents, another brother and two adoptive sisters
from Vietnam. The U.S. government has approved, but the Vietnamese
government has not.
   Nguyen's mother and father were doctors when North Vietnam's
communist government completed its takeover of South Vietnam in
1975.
   They now grow coconuts in Chogao, a farm village 70 miles south
of Ho Chi Minh City, formerly Saigon.
   ``We don't have any future there,'' Nguyen said. ``We never
really get along with the communists and the way the communists
treat the people.''
   Nguyen said he is grateful for the help he has received in the
United States.
   ``Because of all of the people who have given me scholarships,
help and support for the last five years,'' he said. ``I should not
do anything that will disappoint them.''
</TEXT>
