<FIRST>r i AM-EGermany-Allies     11-12 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-EGermany-Allies,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Limits of Allied Control Clear in Breakdown of Berlin Borders</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Germany, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The World War II Allies still have an official
grip on Berlin, but there was little evidence of that during a
tumultuous weekend of wild celebrations.
   No one asked permission from the United States, the Soviet
Union, England or France to punch holes through border barriers,
although security and sovereignty are strictly the affair of the
occupying forces.
   Likewise, the exclusive Allied matter of access to the city was
ignored during the emotional exchange that brought hundreds of
thousands of East Germans to West Berlin.
   Reflecting the upset of order inflicted by the crumbling
borders, U.S. Army Sgt. Terry Ramsey said his unit had suspended
patrolling of the Berlin Wall, where the watchposts were empty.
   ``There's no reason to go because we gather information about
the guards and the towers,'' said Ramsey, who has been stationed in
Berlin for three years. ``There's no one there. So there's no
purpose in the wall patrol.''
   But the four-power control does have effects _ for example,
forcing a wide detour in what would have been a short flight for
West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl from Warsaw to Berlin last week.
   And the Allies would legally have final say over the
reunification of Berlin.
   Under the Potsdam agreement of 1945, the four victorious powers
of World War II parceled out defeated Nazi Germany and the capital,
Berlin, for occupation.
   Sovereignty was granted to the new West German state created out
of the French, British and American occupation zones in 1949, and
the Soviets followed by setting up the Communist state of East
Germany in the remaining zone.
   Berlin has remained under Allied jurisdiction.
   Day-to-day administration of the Western sectors was deeded to a
West Berlin government, and the Soviets gradually relinquished East
Berlin to the installed Communist leadership.
   U.S. Mission spokesman Anthony Sariti explained that the powers
officially remaining with the Allies are over security, access and
provision of services and facilities for the occupying forces.
   The controls define air corridors into the city that limit
commercial aviation access to carriers from France, Britain and the
United States, and highway access is also officially monitored by
the foreign forces.
   That cumbersome air corridor stipulation forced Kohl to detour
through Hamburg on Friday when he flew from the Polish capital of
Warsaw to Berlin. It also prevents the West German national
carrier, Lufthansa, from flying into one of the nation's most
important cities.
</TEXT>
