<HEAD>Police Deny Arrest Made in Shooting of Pregnant Woman and Husband</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police on Sunday denied published reports that
they had arrested a key suspect in last month's shooting of a
pregnant woman and her husband.
   William Bennett, 39, of Boston's Mission Hill section, where the
shootings occurred, was arrested at his girlfriend's home in
suburban Burlington on a traffic violation, Burlington police said
Saturday.
   The Boston Sunday Herald cited unidentified police sources as
saying Bennett was a chief suspect in the shooting that killed
attorney Carol Stuart and her baby and wounded her husband, Charles
Stuart.
   The Boston Sunday Globe also reported that unidentified sources
familiar with the case said police were focusing on Bennett as a
suspect.
   But Joseph Dunford, deputy chief of detectives for Boston
Police, released a statement Sunday saying no arrest had been made
in the Stuart case and declining comment on the Herald article.
   Dunford could not be reached immediately by telephone.
   Pauline Bennett, the mother of the arrested man, said her son
was a suspect in the shooting that drew nationwide attention to
Boston's flaring crime problems.
   ``They say he's a suspect,'' she said. ``He's been in trouble
before. He knew he was a suspect. He was nervous and upset about
it.''
   Burlington police said they had cooperated with Boston police on
Bennett's arrest, and they referred all questions about the
shooting to Boston police.
   ``It was a routine arrest on a traffic warrant,'' Lt. Arnold
Christiansen said. ``We don't have any information related to'' the
Stuart shootings, he said.
   Mrs. Stuart, 30, died after she was shot in the head by a man
who abducted the couple as they were leaving Brigham and Womens'
Hospital, where they had attended a birthing class.
   The infant, Christopher, was delivered by Caesarean section and
clung to life for more than two weeks before succumbing to a
respiratory ailment Thursday. The medical examiner ruled his death
a homicide.
   Charles Stuart, 29, was listed in guarded condition after having
surgery Saturday at Boston City Hospital. Hospital officals would
not give a reason for the surgery.
   Bennett has served separate prison terms for shooting two police
officers, the Sunday Herald reported.
   Charles Stuart told police his assailant shot him because he
thought Stuart was a police officer after seeing Stuart's cellular
car phone.
   Bennett's girlfriend, Faye Nelson, told the Sun of Lowell in a
telephone interview that Bennett was with her when the shootings
occurred.
   ``He didn't do it,'' Nelson said.
