<FIRST>r a AM-People-Sutherland     11-12 0312</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Sutherland,0322</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soprano Sutherland Bows Off U.S. Opera Stage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE CROSS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dame Joan Sutherland bid farewell to the American
opera stage, telling fans she wanted to leave ``a pleasant sound in
your ears.''
   The 63-year-old prima donna's last U.S. performance, in the
title role of ``The Merry Widow,'' was capped by a tribute from
President Bush.
   ``Dame Joan's coloratura soprano echos in the minds of all who
have been privileged to hear her sing,'' Bush wrote in a tribute
presented Saturday to Miss Sutherland on the same stage where she
made her American debut 29 years ago.
   Miss Sutherland clasped her hand to her heart at Bush's words,
then thanked her American fans for their attention over the course
of her stage career, one of the longest and most illustrious in
opera.
   ``I can never forget the wonder of it all when I came to the
U.S., and how pleasant, how wonderful you've all been,'' Miss
Sutherland said.
   She has scheduled only two more opera performances, in ``Die
Fledermaus'' at London's Royal Opera and ``Les Huguenots'' in her
native Australia.
   She plans to continue giving concerts, but said the time had
come to depart the opera stage.
   ``I'd rather leave you with a pleasant sound in your ears than
start croaking too much,'' she said.
   Miss Sutherland said she is retiring so she can spend more time
at her home and garden in Switzerland and with her family. She also
has said it is time for younger singers to get the applause.
   ``I get a little embarrassed now to think that I am the age I am
and still taking up space that could go to a younger person,'' she
said in the recent interview. ``The time has come when it is better
that I am in the audience rather than on the stage.''
</TEXT>
