<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Ashkenazy     11-12 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Ashkenazy,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conductor Makes Triumphant Return to Homeland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vladimir Ashkenazy was cheered Sunday at the
Moscow academy where he once studied as he conducted Britain's
Royal Philharmonic orchestra in the return to his homeland he had
not seen for 26 years.
   Shouts of ``Bravo! Bravo!'' rang through the Grand Hall of the
Moscow Conservatory as the orchestra finished a program that
included works by Russian composers Mussorgsky, Rachmaninov and
Tchaikovsky.
   Ashkenazy, a student at the conservatory when he shared the top
prize in the 1962 Tchaikovsky piano competition, beamed and joined
briefly in the crowd's rhythmic applause.
   The program was the second of two charity concerts by Ashkenazy
and the Royal Philharmonic. Proceeds will help restore cultural
monuments destroyed in last December's earthquake in the southern
Soviet republic of Armenia. About 25,000 people were killed by the
quake.
   Ashkenazy is one of many Soviet artists who left or were
expelled from their native land but have returned to perform in the
freer climate permitted by President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   After his performance in the 1962 Tchaikovsky competition,
Ashkenazy left for a concert tour of Britain and announced in April
1963 that he intended to stay abroad. He returned briefly to Moscow
but left again later in 1963.
   Another famous pianist, Vladimir Horowitz, returned in 1986
after a 61-year absence. When Horowitz died Nov. 5 in New York he
was eulogized by the Soviet Union as an artist whose talent
belonged to the world.
   Ashkenazy put aside his conductor's baton during the first
concert Saturday to play the piano as the Royal Philharmonic
performed Beethoven's Concerto No. 3 for Piano and Orchestra.
   On Sunday, Soviet pianist Andrei Gavrilov, who won the
Tchaikovsky competition 14 years after Ashkenazy, performed as the
orchestra played Rachmaninov's Second Concerto.
   Dozens of people gathered outside the conservatory, one of the
most prestigious concert halls in Moscow, hoping to be able to
purchase a ticket. Tickets sold for up to $19, a large sum compared
to average concert prices in the Soviet Union.
   Soldiers behind metal barricades checked tickets twice before
concert-goers were able to enter the hall, and the tickets were
checked several more times inside.
   Listeners broke into applause when they recognized the first
notes from Tchaikovsky's ``Nutcracker Suite,'' the orchestra's
single encore, and were still applauding when the conductor and
orchestra left the stage after several curtain calls.
</TEXT>
