<FIRST>r i AM-Vatican-Czech     11-12 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Vatican-Czech,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pope Canonizes Czechoslovak Nun, Polish Friar in First TV Ceremony</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II canonized Princess Agnes
of Bohemia, a medieval Czechoslovak nun, on Sunday in the first
papal ceremony broadcast on state television in the Communist
nation.
   The pontiff also formally conferred sainthood on a Polish friar,
Adam Chmielowski.
   More than 9,000 Czechoslovaks, including a government
delegation, packed St. Peter's Basilica to watch the canonization
of the princess who turned nun and laid a framework for social work
in 13th century Bohemia _ a region that became modern
Czechoslovakia.
   The pilgrims paid $300 each for the four-day trip to Rome.
   The live, hour-long broadcast and the unprecedented move of
granting travel visas to Czechoslovak pilgrims reflected a marked
improvement in relations between Prague and the Holy See in recent
months.
   The decision to broadcast the ceremony appeared to be in line
with an official effort to prevent Catholic dissent at a time when
Czechoslovakia's orthodox Communist leaders are becoming
increasingly isolated from shifts toward democracy in other eastern
European countries.
   During the ceremony, the Polish-born pontiff praised Agnes for
her ``Christian faith and heroic charity.''
   Agnes rejected efforts by her parents _ King Premysl Otakar I
and Queen Constance _ to arrange her a royal wedding. Instead she
became a nun in 1234 and established religious hospitals and the
Convent of the Poor Sisters, where she died in 1282.
   John Paul told the crowd they should learn from Agnes' example
of helping others without complaint.
   ``Human history is in continuous movement; times change with the
different generations and with scientific discoveries; new
techniques but also new worries arise on the horizon of human
beings, who are always traveling; but the truth of Christ, who
illuminates and saves, survives the changing events,'' said the
gold-robed pontiff.
   He did not refer specifically to the rapid push toward democracy
in Eastern Europe over recent months or to Czechoslovakia's failure
to embrace the shift.
   But there has been a thaw in the Vatican's relations with the
Soviet bloc and, after years of bitterness and contention, Prague
agreed to the appointment of four new bishops this year.
   However, seven out of thirteen diocese in Czechoslovakia are
still vacant.
   Also canonized Sunday was Chmielowski, known as ``Brother
Albert.'' He was a 19th century painter of religious themes who
founded hostels for the poor and homeless. He became a Franciscan
friar and established a congregation of friars.
   He helped found 21 religious houses before dying in 1916.
</TEXT>
