<FIRST>r i AM-Egypt     11-12 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt,0425</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mubarak Calls For Measures To Combat Trade Gap, Unemployment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hosni Mubarak called for measures
to combat a trade gap, unemployment and sluggish productivity among
government-owned industries, but he rejected calls to sell off
companies to the private sector.
   In a nationally broadcast policy speech Saturday marking the
inauguration of a new session of the People's Assembly, Mubarak
devoted most of his 90-minute speech to the economy and how to
enact reform.
   For months, Egyptian officials have been discussing the need to
dismantle part of the public sector, whose factories range from
producing iron and steel to clothes. Mubarak called for freer
management of government-owned industries but he refused to
consider privatization.
   ``The freeing of the public sector is a pure Egyptian necessity
for the interest of the national economy,'' he said. ``The issue is
not selling the public sector or changing its ownership, but the
issue is supporting it and increasing its capability so that it
will produce more.''
   The president said the nation needed to narrow its $4.5 billion
gap between foreign exchange and spending on imports by increasing
production and modernizing the industrial and agricultural sectors.
   ``Continuation of this gap would have dire consequences,
touching the country and all citizens,'' Mubarak told the 458-seat
house where his National Democratic Party holds an overwhelming
majority.
   Mubarak ruled out using foreign loans to bridge the gap. The
country's foreign debt totals about $44 billion.
   Mubarak indicated private business must help in tackling
unemployment. Official figures show about 2 million university
graduates and laborers are without jobs.
   ``We put the unemployment problem at the top of our priorities
because we understand the importance of opening new productive job
opportunities ... but the government cannot face this problem
alone,'' Mubarak said.
   Mubarak, who took office eight years ago, inherited most of the
country's economic woes from late President Anwar Sadat's open-door
policy and late President Gamal Abdel Nasser's socialist regime.
   Roughly one-fourth of Egypt's foreign debt is owed to the United
States. Under pressure from the U.S.-dominated International
Monetary Fund, Cairo began economic changes in 1987 that included
increasing exports, reducing imports and fusing several foreign
exchange rates into a single, more realistic one.
   The reforms enabled Egypt, with IMF help, to reschedule debts of
about $8 billion. Talks are under way with the fund on further
changes to permit rescheduling $5 billion in other loans.
</TEXT>
