<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLOOMINGTON, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here's what looks like another first: A
husband and wife team of federal appellate judges.
   Sheldon Jay Plager and Irene H. Nagel say as nearly as they can
tell, they made U.S. judicial history when Plager, an Indiana
University law school professor, was sworn in Saturday as a member
of the U.S. Court of Appeals in Washington. Nagel has served as a
member of the U.S. Sentencing Commission since 1985.
   Plager said he hasn't conducted his own research on whether they
are unique, but: ``I suspect it's true,'' he said.
   Plager was sworn in Saturday night in a ceremony at his
Bloomington home.
   Plager, 58, was dean of the Indiana University Law School until
1984. Since then he has taught part-time in his specialties of
environmental, property and administrative law.
   Nagel has been on the law school faculty since 1973, teaching
criminal law. She has taught part time since her federal
appointment.
