<FIRST>r a AM-MilitaryJetCrash     11-12 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Military Jet Crash,0264</SECOND>
<HEAD>Planes Flying From Base Where Jet Hit Apartment Complex</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SMYRNA, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jets resumed flying from Dobbins Air Force
Base north of Atlanta on Sunday, three days after an attack plane
crashed into an apartment complex short of the runway, killing two
people.
   Petty Officer Linda Herring said the Navy considered Thursday's
crash an isolated incident and was not suspending any flight
operations.
   ``If an investigation indicates that changes should be made, we
will of course make them,'' she said.
   The investigation of the crash is expected to take at least 30
days.
   Officials at the Naval Air Station Atlanta, which is adjacent to
Dobbins about 15 miles north of Atlanta, said earlier that pilots
were taking a few days off from training flights in the wake of the
crash.
   The pilot of the A-7E Corsair II, Lt. Cmdr. Robert M. Conlyn
Jr., 37, remained in critical condition Sunday at Kennestone
Hospital. Conlyn was the only person aboard the unarmed plane and
ejected just before it crashed into the apartment complex two miles
short of the runway.
   Jacquelyn Padovani, 5, who suffered burns over about half of her
body, was in critical condition at Grady Memorial Hospital on
Sunday. Her pregnant mother, 28-year-old Margie Padovani, died
Friday night at the hospital from burns, and Richard Dick, 24, died
in his incinerated apartment.
   Smyrna officials said the crash destroyed 12 of the complex's 76
units and damaged another 20. Residents received more than $140,000
in interim compensation from the Navy on Saturday.
