<FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-12 0230</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snow in Montana, Record Heat in Parts of South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pacific Northwest was hit by snow and cold rain Sunday with
nearly a foot of snow piled up in parts of Montana while
unseasonably warm weather in parts of the South and West broke high
temperature records.
   There was snow Sunday in the Cascade Mountains in Washington and
in western North Dakota with snow expected to extend into northern
Minnesota.
   Rainshowers extended from western Oregon to western Montana.
   Clouds and a few snow showers were over the Great Lakes region
and northern New England. Sunny skies prevailed across the rest of
the nation.
   Warm weather prevailed in the south-central and the southeastern
U.S. Sunny skies and southerly winds pushed temperatures into the
70s and 80s in the southern Plains region.
   Temperatures warmed into the 70s and 80s from the lower half of
the Mississippi Valley to the southern half of the Atlantic Coast
region.
   There were record high temperatures in: Athens, Ga., 81 degrees;
Augusta, Ga., 85 degrees; Charleston, S.C., 83 degrees;
Chattanooga, Tenn., 81 degrees; Charlotte, N.C., 81 degrees;
Cheyenne, Wyo., 70 degrees; Denver, 75 degrees; Goodland, Kans., 77
degrees; Pueblo, Colo., 80 degrees; Raleigh, N.C., 79 degrees;
Scottsbluff, Neb., 79 degrees; and Wilmington, N.C., 85 degrees.
   The low for the Lower 48 states Sunday was 5 degrees at
Gunnison, Colo.
