<FIRST>r e BC-Theater     11-12 0762</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Theater,0777</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Grand Hotel,' A New Musical, Opens on Broadway</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: No PMs planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The time is 1928, the place Berlin. The
Depression is only a year away, and Hitler waits to seize power in
Germany. But at the Grand Hotel, people are more concerned with
other, more important things _ like life, death, love, money.
   They are the subjects of ``Grand Hotel,'' the intoxicating,
evocative new musical that swept into Broadway's Martin Beck
Theater on Sunday night under the extraordinary guidance of Tommy
Tune.
   With Jerome Robbins' preoccupation with ballet and the deaths of
Michael Bennett, Bob Fosse and Gower Champion, Tune stands alone as
the foremost director and choreographer of Broadway musicals.
Although their approaches differed greatly, these men are linked by
their ability to make musicals move, to create productions that
soar through song, dance and story.
   And ``Grand Hotel,'' based on the Vicki Baum novel and the
famous MGM film starring Greta Garbo and John Barrymore, moves with
a fluidity that approaches the cinematic.
   Through the hotel's ever-revolving front door swirl a half dozen
characters whose stories will be played out before the evening's
two hours are over. All of them are introduced in a dazzling
opening number, ``The Grand Parade.''
   Grushinskaya, the aging ballerina, is on yet another farewell
tour, tended by her devoted companion, Raffaela. A young baron,
trying to find a way to pay his debts, contemplates stealing the
ballerina's jewels. Preysing, an industrialist, attempts to close a
big business deal before his career is ruined. Flaemmchen, a
secretary, stuck in a drab, dead-end job, longs to go to Hollywood
and become a movie star. Kringelein, a timid, terminally ill
accountant, discovers how to enjoy life in his dying moments.
   The book, written by Luther Davis with apparently an uncredited
assist from Peter Stone, telescopes their stories with grace and
wit without sacrificing characterization.
   Much of the score by Robert Wright and George Forrest was
augmented or revised by Maury Yeston, the composer and lyricist of
``Nine.'' Who wrote what is documented laboriously in the program.
Regardless of authorship, the music and lyrics fit together well,
particularly the period pastiches that suggest the sounds of the
late 1920s.
   The cast sings and dances with authority. As the ballerina,
Liliane Montevecchi is surprisingly funny, although she is not much
of an actress. The woman has a show biz snappiness that works well,
especially when she tears through the show's most heavily Parisian
number, ``Bonjour Amour.'' David Carroll, blessed with the
strongest voice in the cast, earns applause with the baron's
high-powered love song, ``Love Can't Happen.''
   Flaemmchen is a Germanic Betty Boop and, as played by Jane
Krakowski, becomes an utterly captivating creature, particularly
when she is dancing a Charleston with Kringelein (Michael Jeter).
   Jeter is astonishing in a second Charleston, ``We'll Take a
Glass Together,'' in which the loose-limbered little man dances his
way over the hotel bar. And Timothy Jerome, the greedy
industrialist, sings what could be show's best song, ``The Crooked
Path,'' with great glee. Karen Akers as the ballerina's morose
confidante is saddled with the musical's gloomiest numbers, but she
still manages to create a character.
   Tune interwines their tales brilliantly. The glamorous
introduction is interspersed with a hard, proletarian lament,
``Some Have, Some Have Not,'' from the hotel's scullery workers.
The musical and dance numbers blend with a flawless precision,
rarely stopping for star turns by the performers. There is a
dramatic tango near the end of the musical, but it serves to
underscore an important plot development rather than interrupt the
show.
   That seems to be the hallmark of Tune's sophisticated approach.
The show has enormous style that never slips to mere showiness. It
recalls such landmark musicals as ``Cabaret,'' ``Follies'' and even
``Evita,'' in which everything served the story.
   Tony Walton's stationary, two-tiered setting, composed of what
look like glass pillars, puts the orchestra above the action on the
second level. It's a restrained but expensive-looking environment
that allows the playing area to be set aside for dancing. Much of
the hotel's activity is mimed, from the telephone operators
answering calls, to the partying in the hotel bar, even down to the
workings of the washroom attendants.
   ``People come, people go, but nothing seems to change,'' says a
world-weary doctor, the hotel's one permanent resident, played with
a bitter ferocity by John Wylie. In ``Grand Hotel,'' Tune and
company have put an entire world on stage and in the process,
created a daring, provocative piece of musical theater.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
