<FIRST>u i AM-Kohl 1stLd-Writethru   11-12 0577</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kohl, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0671,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Busy Kohl Offers Olive Branch to Poland</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Kohl meeting in Warsaw with
Jaruzelski, other leaders. Pickup 6th pvs, `Bishop Alfons...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl
embraced Poland's prime minister in a sign of reconciliation
between the two nations during a Mass Sunday in a village on former
German territory.
   About 5,000 worshipers applauded the gesture by Kohl and Prime
Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki in Krzyzowa. During World War II
members of the anti-Nazi resistance met in Krzyzowa, known in
German as Kreisau.
   Dense fog shrouded Warsaw, forcing Kohl to travel six hours by
bus rather than plane to reach Krzyzowa after he resumed his visit
to Poland _ interrupted by a brief trip home to discuss
developments in East Germany.
   Kohl returned to Warsaw Sunday evening for talks with Communist
President Wojciech Jaruzelski; Mazowiecki, a former Solidarity
activist, and Polish Foreign Minister Krzysztof Skubiszewski.
   Hans Klein, Kohl's spokesman, told reporters afterward that the
talks had focused on East Germany's opening of the Berlin Wall and
other borders to the West. He characterized the talks as
``unusually intense and open.''
   Poland has welcomed the new East German freedoms, but the
prospect of reuniting the two Germanys is met with suspicion in a
nation overrun by Germany in World War II and still insecure about
its western border.
   On Sunday, the West German leader _ the first to visit Poland
since 1977 _ sought to erase the bitter Nazi German legacy.
   Bishop Alfons Nossol celebrated the 90-minute Roman Catholic
service in Polish and in German, saying it could serve as
reconciliation between the Germans and Poles.
   ``We have heard in the sermon,'' Kohl said, that ``we should
never forget history, but we also have to learn from history. I
think it was just this moment of learning of history. We have
greeted one another in the sign of reconciliaton.''
   West German diplomats in Warsaw said Kohl attached great
symbolic importance to the visit to Krzyzowa. Kohl appeared moved
when he embraced Mazowiecki after the congregation was asked to
give the sign of peace to one another.
   One-third of all current Polish territory was German before
World War II. An estimated 80,000 ethnic Germans remain, mostly in
the former German territories of Silesia and East Prussia.
   Polish-German relations in the region have been strained since
the Nazi invasion of Poland in 1939. Millions of Germans were
expelled after the regions were awarded to Poland after the war.
Those displaced Germans remain a strong political force in West
Germany.
   Reporters at the Mass and Polish radio said about 5,000 people
attended the service, which was broadcast on television. Some held
banners in German saying, ``We demand German schools and church
services,'' and ``Helmut you are our chancellor too.''
   Mazowiecki, the first non-Communist leader in the Soviet bloc,
appealed for greater ``brotherhood'' between Germans and Poles.
   Although a 1970 treaty pledges West Germany's respect of the
Oder and Neisse rivers as Poland's western border, West German
conservatives have recently suggested seeking reunification within
pre-war borders, which include large areas of present-day Poland.
   After the Mass, Kohl was to travel to Czestochowa, the holiest
shrine in Poland, before returning to the capital for a meeting
with President Wojciech Jaruzelski.
   During Kohl's trip, the two sides signed eight agreements. They
include one for $1.5 billion in economic assistance from West
Germany.
</TEXT>
