<HEAD>FBI Says Attempted Abduction May Be Linked to Missing Boy Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The FBI is investigating a possible
connection between an attempted kidnapping outside Minneapolis last
week and the abduction of 11-year-old Jacob Wetterling last month,
an FBI spokesman said Sunday.
   A 10-year-old boy was riding home on his bicycle Wednesday
evening in the suburb of New Brighton when a stranger ordered him
to get into his car, spokesman Byron Gigler said. The boy rode away
and his mother saw the man's car speed off, he said.
   A sketch of the man based on the boy's description matches two
sketches of a man seen acting suspiciously at a store in St.
Joseph, 70 miles northwest of Minneapolis, shortly before
Wetterling was abducted Oct. 22, Gigler said.
   ``All three sketches bear some resemblance to the same man,'' he
said.
   They depict a man described as white, 6 feet tall, about 200
pounds, in his 50s, with a large build, white hair and a receding
hair line.
   The New Brighton boy's mother didn't get a good look at the
suspect's car because it was dark and the car was speeding, Gigler
said.
   Jacob Wetterling was abducted at gunpoint near his home as he
was returning from the convenience store with his brother and a
friend.
   Stearns County Sheriff Charlie Grafft said investigators have
received more than 12,000 tips from around the country regarding
the disappearance.
