<HEAD>Republican Governors Say Abortion Issue Won't Beat Them in 1990</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: TOPS with 9 grafs to include comments from news conference;
edits to conform and picks up pvs 3rd graf bgng ``Fifteen of ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HILTON HEAD ISLAND, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican governors gathered
Sunday to take political stock after the party's 1989 setbacks, and
their leaders said that with better candidates and better handling,
the GOP can avoid trouble on the abortion issue in 1990.
   Three of the governors agreed at an opening night news
conference that Republican candidates should spell out clear
positions on the issue and avoid being typecast as anti-abortion.
   Gov. Carroll A. Campbell Jr. of South Carolina, the conference
host, said Republicans running in 1989 allowed themselves to be
cornered on the issue by the news media and by their Democratic
opponents.
   ``The problem with Republicans is that they have not gone out in
advance and told the public what they believe in,'' `Campbell said.
He said the Democrats defined the issue in their own terms this
year.
   ``You'll beat nothing with something every time you put it on
the table,'' he said.
   Gov. Mike Hayden of Kansas, chairman of the Republican Governors
Association, said this year's elections point to the need for
aggressive efforts to recruit strong GOP candidates in 1990. Asked
whether he was suggesting that the Republicans who lost last
Tuesday weren't strong candidates, Hayden said ``Well, they didn't
win.''
   Gov. John Ashcroft of Missouri, the vice chairman, also sought
to play down the issue, saying the political trouble is at the
extremes, and that the anti-abortion plank of the 1988 Republican
platform won't define the positions GOP candidates for governor
take in 1990.
   Vice President Dan Quayle and Lee Atwater, the party chairman,
were the featured political performers at the governors's two-day
resort conference.
   It opened Sunday with several of the governors, and Quayle,
playing golf in advance of formal sessions planned Monday and
Tuesday.
   Fifteen of the 22 Republican governors were due to attend the
annual conference. That overall number will go down by one when New
Jersey switches hands with the inauguration of a Democrat next year.
   Republicans were defeated there and in Virginia, where the
incumbent is a Democrat, in last Tuesday's off-year balloting. The
Virginia election was the closest in state history, and a recount
is likely.
   Democrats claimed major headway in elections across the nation
and the Republicans could only say, as President Bush did, wait
until next year.
   Quayle's keynote address at the conference on Monday is likely
to look toward the next campaign, when 36 states will elect
governors, 34 will choose senators and all 435 House seats will be
at stake.
   Atwater will concentrate on the politics of reapportionment in
his report to the governors. The state governments shaped in the
1990 elections will be in charge of reapportioning House seats on
the basis of next year's census, and Republicans fear that the
Democrats who have controlled the House for 35 years may draw
district lines that will strengthen that advantage.
   The governors also are to hear reports on the twin problems of
crime and drugs, from Attorney General Dick Thornburgh and William
Bennett, director of the Office of National Drug Control Policy.
   Their final conference session on Tuesday is to deal with
education.
</TEXT>
