<FIRST>r f AM-IslamicConference-IBM     11-12 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Islamic Conference-IBM,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan-Islamic Organization Calls for Blacklisting IBM</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The 46-member Organization of
Islamic Conference on Sunday asked all its member states to boycott
International Business Machines Corp. for its alleged plans to
supply Israel with computer technology that would help the country
make a hydrogen bomb.
   An OIC statement said the American computer company ``was
participating in the production of an advanced computer system for
Israel that will be used in its hydrogen bomb project and which
will also help in Israel's long and medium-range missiles.''
   The statement did not explain what led the organization to
believe the deal has been concluded. There have been reports that
IBM was only studying an Israeli request for the purchase of
sophisticated computers for academic purposes.
   A spokesman for IBM could not be reached for comment Sunday. A
person who answered the main number at the company's Armonk, N.Y.,
headquarters said he could not contact a spokesman.
   The statement from the Jiddah-based organization said ``such a
serious act'' will jeopardize the peace process in the Middle East
as well as international peace and security.
   The OIC has been emulating the pattern of the 22-member Arab
League in drawing up a blacklist of foreign companies whose
dealings with Israel it believes will help prop up the Jewish
state's economy or military effort.
   Arab press reports have said that the Arab League's boycott
office, which is based in Damascus, Syria, was checking on IBM's
alleged involvement in Israel's plans for manufacturing a hydrogen
bomb. The reports said the company will be blacklisted if the
cooperation became a fact.
   A U.S. government interagency team has been debating a
2-year-old request to grant licenses to export three supercomputers
to Israel.
   Arab press reports said the Israelis were interested in IBM and
Cray Research Inc. computers.
</TEXT>
