<DOCNO> AP891112-0084 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-12-89 1752EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-BigThreeChairmen     11-12 0649</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Big Three Chairmen,0670</SECOND>
<HEAD>Poling First in New Chairmen Announcements</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just who will be leading the nation's Big Three
automakers in the 1990s is clearing up, but only temporarily.
   Ford Motor Co. said last week that Vice Chairman Harold Poling
will become head of the nation's No. 2 automaker on March 1, when
Chairman Donald Petersen retires.
   But there's a catch of sorts. Poling, 64, will have the job for
just three years.
   ``That's kind of weird,'' analyst Kathleen Heaney of Nikko
Securities Co. International Inc. in New York said Friday after the
succession was announced. ``So much for the old, predictable Ford.''
   Most of the speculation centers on Allan Gilmour, who on Friday
was named the next president of Ford Automotive Group, the
company's vehicle-making operation.
   ``I think this (three years) is a period of time which the
company is going to use to groom Mr. Gilmour,'' said analyst Scott
Merlis of Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. in New York.
   Succession speculation at Ford is likely to continue for the
next three years. It's a little clearer, at least for the long
term, at General Motors Corp. and Chrysler Corp.
   In a reorganization announced earlier this year, Gerald
Greenwald was named a vice chairman at the No. 3 U.S. automaker,
making him the odds-on replacement for Lee Iacocca, whose contract
with Chrysler expires in early 1991.
   At GM, a board of directors' task force has been looking this
year for a successor to Chairman Roger Smith, who leaves office in
late 1990. GM President Robert Stempel has been mentioned as the
favorite, but some bets are being put on Executive Vice President
F. Alan Smith, no relation to the current chairman.
   In most discussions of succession in automakers' corner offices,
there's usually talk about whether the candidate is a ``car guy''
or a ``bean counter'' _ that is, an executive who came up through
the company's product or finance operations.
   At GM, the debate is clearest.
   Stempel, 56, joined the automaker's Oldsmobile Division as a
detailer in the chassis design department. He stayed in design or
engineering operations en route to heading up the
Buick-Oldsmobile-Cadillac Group in January 1984 and moving on to
become the company's president and chief operating officer in
September 1987.
   Stempel refuses to talk about who the next chairman will be. GM
spokesmen set a ground rule for reporters wishing to interview
Stempel that no questions be asked about who will succeed the
chairman.
   Alan Smith, 58, was hired in June 1956 in the GM treasurer's
office in New York as a trainee and rose through the financial
sector, as did Roger Smith. Alan Smith became executive vice
president for finance in January 1981.
   Some of the blame for GM's falling market share has been laid on
Roger Smith for being too much of a ``bean counter'' and not enough
of a ``car guy.''
   Merlis said the nod should go to Stempel partly because GM's
board ``has taken so much abuse about finance guys being in there.''
   Most of Iacocca's early experience was in product development at
Ford before he joined Chrysler as president in 1978, when the
company faced bleak financial times.
   He led Chrysler's efforts to secure loans and federal guarantees
that eventually bailed out the company. Greenwald came to Chrysler
as the company's controller shortly after Iacocca did.
   There's a common element in each of the potential chairmen. Each
was in a leadership position when the auto industry took a serious
dive in the early 1980s. And each has had a hand in bringing the
Big Three back to profitability.
   ``All of the leadership in the auto industry,'' Merlis said,
``reached the top of the organizations when we had experienced the
worst automotive recession in postwar history.
   ``There's no better training than to drive through hell in an
automotive depression,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
